    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "There are two main reasons Brownie handles networks the way it does:\r\n\r\n* Defining networks within a project's config file means you have to define them for every single project you create. It also creates challenges launching Brownie and connecting to a network when there is no active project.\r\n* How you connect to mainnet might not be the same as how I connect to mainnet.  If the networks are defined within a config file, it creates challenges with version control when multiple people are collaborating on the same project\r\n\r\nI do feel that the current CLI setup is kinda clunky, but I think the approach of per-project network definitions is worse :laughing:  You can edit `~/.brownie/network-config.yaml` directly as a workaround to using the CLI.",
